In 1 468 a visitation of the priory was held by R. Warenn, official of Archbishop Tregury. Prior William Stewnot and Richard Cristor (Christopher) sub-prior, and four canons, attended, and as far as we can judge from the imperfect abstract in Archbishop Tregury's Regis· try, no cause of complaint appeared against any member of the body.

The success of Edward IV. must have excited hopes of royal favour in the prior and canons of All Hallows: claiming, as the heir

of the De Burghs, Ulster and Connaught, and possessed in the right of the Mortimers os the liberty of Meath, this Prince must have felt a persona] interest in the country ; his father had resided in it for some time and had not only won the hearts of the great lords of Meath, whose fidelity to the supposed blood of their hereditary seudal lord was shewn at the battle of Stoke, but had gained also the support of the great family of the Geraldines, the ancient benefactors of the priory.
